    <h2>The Quick Answer: 4 Cups in a Quart</h2>
    <p>In the US customary measurement system, one quart contains exactly 4 cups. This is a defined relationship, not an approximation. The word "quart" comes from the Latin "quartus" (meaning fourth), because a quart is one-fourth of a gallon. Since a gallon contains 16 cups and a quart is one-fourth of a gallon, the math is straightforward: 16 / 4 = 4 cups per quart.</p>
    <p>Here is the full chain from gallons down to fluid ounces for quick reference: 1 gallon = 4 quarts = 8 pints = 16 cups = 128 fluid ounces. Each step involves a factor of 2 (cups to pints, pints to quarts) except the quart-to-gallon step, which is a factor of 4. Memorizing this chain gives you the ability to convert between any two units instantly.</p>

    <h2>Complete Kitchen Conversion Table: Gallon to Teaspoon</h2>
    <p>The following table shows the complete US customary volume hierarchy from the largest common unit (gallon) down to the smallest (teaspoon). This is the single most useful table to have in your kitchen.</p>
